quran[24]{c,v,t,f}:
53,45,"and He it is Who created the two kinds, the male and the female,"
53,46,"from a drop of sperm when it was emitted, {1}",footnotes:1:For explanation
53,47,"and that it is for Him to grant the second life, {1}",footnotes:1:When this verse is read with the two preceding verses
53,48,"that He it is Who bestowed wealth and riches, {1}",footnotes:1:Different meanings have been given by the lexicographers and commentators of the word aqna as used in the original. According to Qatadah
53,49,"that He is the Lord of Sirius, {1}",footnotes:1:Shiera is the brightest star in the heavens
53,50,"that He it is Who destroyed the ancient 'Ad, {1}",footnotes:1:Aad Ula signifies the ancient Aad to whom the Prophet Houd (peace be upon him) had been appointed as a Prophet. When those people were inflicted with the torment in consequence of denying the Prophet Houd (peace be upon him)
53,51,"and Thamud, leaving no trace of them,"
53,52,"and that He it is Who destroyed the people of Noah before for they were much given to iniquity and transgression."
53,53,"And He brought perdition upon the subverted cities"
53,54,"and caused them to be covered with that which He covered them with. {1}",footnotes:1:“The subverted settlements”: the settlements of the people of Lot
53,55,"So, {1} which of your Lord's bounties will you doubt?” {2}",footnotes:1:According to some commentators this sentence is also a part of the resume of the Books of the Prophets Abraham and Moses
53,56,"This is a warning among the warnings of yore. {1}",footnotes:1:The words in the original are: Hadha nadhir-un-minan- nudhur-il-ula. The commentators have expressed three points of view in the explanation of this sentence. First
53,57,"The imminent Hour has drawn near, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,58,"and none but Allah can avert it. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,59,"Will you, then, wonder at this? {1}",footnotes:1:The word hadh-al-Hadith as used in the original
53,60,"Will you laugh at it rather than weep? {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,61,"Will you occupy yourselves simply in merriment? {1}",footnotes:1:Two meanings have been given of the word samidun by the lexicographers.
53,62,"Prostrate yourselves before Allah, and serve Him. {1}",footnotes:1:According to Imam Abu Hanifah
54,1,"The Hour of Resurrection drew near and the moon split asunder. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
54,2,"(Regardless of any Signs these people see), they turn away and say: “This is an ongoing sorcery.” {1}",footnotes:1:The words sihr-um mustamirr of the text can have several meanings:
54,3,"They also gave the lie to (the splitting asunder of the moon) and only followed their desires. {1} Yet everything is destined to reach an end. {2}",footnotes:1:That is
54,4,"Surely there came to them narratives (of the ancient nations) that should suffice to deter (them from transgression),"
54,5,"narratives that are full of consummate wisdom. But warnings do not avail them."
54,6,"So turn away from them, (O Prophet). {1} On the Day when a caller shall call them to a thing most terrible, {2}",footnotes:1:Another meaning can be “an unknown thing”
